<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-06-20T01:34:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-06-20T01:34:00-05:00" n="254" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d254">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 661.939/15</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Harbin</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MCK1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Moser</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Harbin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-06-20T15:00:00+08:26"><hi rend="italic">June 20,
                                            1918, 3 p.m.</hi></date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received June 20, 12.02
                                    p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Commissioner Chinese Customs informed consular body to-day of
                                complete removal of embargo against export to Russians’ territory by
                                Chinese Government. Please inform War Trade Board that as greatest
                                bulk of imports to Harbin are intended for sale to buyers in Russia
                                and there is now no means for controlling transactions of any of the
                                merchant firms at Harbin, the consulate can not accept any
                                responsibility for the destination of any goods shipped to Harbin or
                                offer any assurance that they may not fall into the hands of the
                                enemy.</p>
                            <pb facs="0231" n="181" xml:id="pg_181"/>
                            <p>An identical telegram, in which I could not join, was sent to-day by
                                the Japanese, British, and French consular representatives to their
                                respective Ministers at Peking . …</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed><persName corresp="#p_MCK1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Moser</hi></persName></signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>